129. 30. noque all . . . potuissent. This pluperfect is often used in this way instead of the imperfect, inasmuch as the possibility of the thing is represented as the condition which must be fulfilled before the thing itself can take place. [The possibility of happening would seem to be a necessary condition to the actual happening of any thing whatever 3 otherwise it would never happen. The idea of possibility lies here not in the tense, but in the very signification of the word potuissent; and the difference between potuissent and possent is that the former represents the possibility as existing at some earlier time. The idea seems to be that if it were not for the care of men sheep not only would not now be able to exist and flourish, but would never
